cell("markdown","---\n## Phase −1 — Theoretical Foundation\n\n### Non-Uniform Distributions\n> 📖 *From Algorithms Ch. 5:* Flipping a fair coin is sampling from `[0.5, 0.5]`. What if we want to roll a die with 2 red, 1 blue, 1 green, and 1 yellow face? We must sample from `[0.4, 0.2, 0.2, 0.2]`.\n\n### Roulette Wheel Selection\nTo sample an index from an arbitrary distribution:\n1. Turn the distribution into a **cumulative distribution**. (e.g. `[0.4, 0.6, 0.8, 1.0]`)\n2. Sample a random float $r$ between 0 and 1. (e.g. `r = 0.63`)\n3. Find the **first index** in the cumulative distribution that is $\\geq r$. (0.8 is the first value $\\geq$ 0.63, so we pick index 2)."),
cell("markdown","### Comprehension Check ✅\n1. Given the cumulative distribution `[0.1, 0.5, 0.9, 1.0]`, which index is chosen if $r = 0.45$?\n2. What must the final value in a cumulative probability distribution always be?\n\n<details><summary>💡 Answers</summary>\n\n1. Index 1 (the value 0.5 is the first value $\\geq$ 0.45).\n2. It must be 1.0, because the sum of all probabilities must be 100%.\n</details>"),
