cell("markdown","# Algorithms 06: Cartesian Product\n\n**Learning Objectives:**\n1. Understand the Cartesian Product of multiple arrays\n2. Understand the danger of array-referencing vs array-copying in Python\n3. Implement an iterative Cartesian product generator from scratch\n\n**Prerequisites:** Algorithms 01\n**Estimated time:** 60 minutes\n**Textbook:** *Justin Skycak — Intro to Algorithms & Machine Learning* Chapter 6"),
COLAB,
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase −1 — Theoretical Foundation\n\n### What is a Cartesian Product?\n> 📖 *From Algorithms Ch. 6:* The Cartesian product constructs all the points whose elements occupy the given ranges. \n\nFor example, if we have ranges `[1, 2]` and `['A', 'B']`, the Cartesian product is:\n`[[1, 'A'], [1, 'B'], [2, 'A'], [2, 'B']]`.\n\n### The Algorithm\n1. Create an array initialized with an empty point: `points = [[]]`.\n2. For each range in your input:\n   - Create a `new_points` array.\n   - For every point currently in `points`, and every item in the current range, append the item to the point and save it to `new_points`.\n   - Update `points = new_points`.\n\n### The Array Copying Trap\nIn Python, if `a = [1]`, doing `b = a` does NOT copy the array. Both `a` and `b` point to the exact same list in memory. Doing `b.append(2)` will modify `a` as well!\nTo make a new copy, you must use `b = a[:]` or `b = a.copy()` or `b = list(a)`."),
cell("markdown","### Comprehension Check ✅\n1. If you take the Cartesian product of three arrays of sizes 2, 3, and 4, how many items will be in the result?\n2. What is the value of `a` after this code runs? `a = [1]; b = a; b.append(2)`\n\n<details><summary>💡 Answers</summary>\n\n1. $2 \\times 3 \\times 4 = 24$ items.\n2. `a = [1, 2]`. Because `b` is just a reference to `a`, appending to `b` mutates the underlying list.\n</details>"),
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase 0 — Math Foundation Practice\n\n### 🎯 Your Turn: The Copy Trap\nWrite a small code snippet to demonstrate the array referencing trap. Create `a`, make `b` point to it, mutate `b`, and print `a` to show it changed. Then show the correct way to make a copy."),
