cell("markdown","### Chalkboard Defense\nWhy is the space complexity of `calc_cartesian_product` equal to $O(K^N)$ (assuming $N$ arrays of size $K$), and how could you mitigate memory exhaustion using Python **generators** (`yield`)?\n\n<details><summary>💡 Sketch</summary>\nIt builds the entire list of $K^N$ combinations in memory at once. \nIf you use `yield` (a generator), you can lazily evaluate the combinations one at a time. This reduces the memory footprint (space complexity) to $O(N)$ — enough to store a single point and the generator state — while the time complexity remains $O(K^N)$.\n</details>\n\n---\n📚 **Next:** Algorithms 07 (Brute Force Cryptography)")
